</div>



<div class="wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2593.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" width="768" height="1024" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2593-768x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-23718" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2593-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2593-225x300.jpg 225w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2593.jpg 960w" sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Frost Library</figcaption></figure>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column is-layout-flow wp-block-column-is-layout-flow">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2582.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" width="768" height="1024" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2582-768x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-23716" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2582-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2582-225x300.jpg 225w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/thumbnail_IMG_2582.jpg 960w" sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Frost Library Study room</figcaption></figure>
</div>
</div>



<p><strong>Mila:</strong> Bronfman library, it's really quiet but also has a lot of natural lighting so you don't end up feeling sleepy and can focus properly. There are also tables with lighting and then smaller individual study spots so plenty to choose from.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/library_bronfman_study.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" width="1024" height="683" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/library_bronfman_study-1024x683.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-23687" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/library_bronfman_study-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/library_bronfman_study-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/library_bronfman_study-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/library_bronfman_study.jpg 1872w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Bronfman Library</figcaption></figure>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Best place to relax</h2>



<p><strong>Taylor:</strong> My favorite study space to relax is in the Bronfman Library lounge because the chairs are comfortable and there is a nice view.</p>



<p><strong>Musaddiq: </strong>Marsden Salon. The space has cozy environment, comfortable furnishings and great wall art.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_lounge.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_lounge-1024x682.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-23721" width="668" height="445" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_lounge-1024x682.jpg 1024w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_lounge-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_lounge.jpg 1315w" sizes="(max-width: 668px) 100vw, 668px" /></a></figure></div>


<p><strong>Mila: </strong>Scott library, study spaces on the balconies - can talk at a normal volume, can simply sit on the floor, not necessarily at the study carrels</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/SCott-desks-.png"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/SCott-desks--1024x679.png" alt="" class="wp-image-23725" width="613" height="406" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/SCott-desks--1024x679.png 1024w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/SCott-desks--300x199.png 300w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/SCott-desks-.png 1032w" sizes="(max-width: 613px) 100vw, 613px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Scott Library 5th floor</figcaption></figure></div>


<p><strong>Timi: </strong>Marsden Salon, this is because it is a small area where I can relax on the couch<br></p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Best place for group projects or group studying</h2>



<p><strong>Taylor:</strong> If I have a group project, I like to book the group rooms at either Bronfman or Steacie library because they are more enclosed and less prone to noise distractions than the ones in Scott.</p>



<p><strong>Mila: </strong>Scott library 2nd floor - not fully expected to be quiet, can comfortably chat, usually plenty of space where you can sit together if needed.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignleft size-full is-resized"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_commons-724x483-3-edited-1.jpeg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_commons-724x483-3-edited-1.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-23698" width="1087" height="612" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_commons-724x483-3-edited-1.jpeg 723w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/library_commons-724x483-3-edited-1-300x169.jpeg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 1087px) 100vw, 1087px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Collaboratory at Scott Library</figcaption></figure></div>


<p><strong>Musaddiq: </strong>Collaboratory. It's spacious, has ample natural light and is very happening place which gets you going too!<br><strong>Guillaume: </strong>At Frost, the study rooms are ideal for group work. They provide an enclosed space where we can talk, put our ideas on the board or connect our laptop to the screen.</p>



<p></p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Best place to work when you have a break in your schedule</h2>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignleft size-full is-resized"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-2023-03-01-at-12.33.09-PM.png"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-2023-03-01-at-12.33.09-PM.png" alt="" class="wp-image-23762" width="359" height="237" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-2023-03-01-at-12.33.09-PM.png 936w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-2023-03-01-at-12.33.09-PM-300x198.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 359px) 100vw, 359px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Maps Library study area</figcaption></figure></div>


<p><strong>Taylor:</strong> When I have to do work between classes, I like to go to the back area of the first floor of Scott Library because not many people go back there. It's nice to have "your own" space to get things done.</p>



<p><strong>Mila:</strong> Scott library, it's in the center and close to where all my classes are, and I can usually find a table to sit at and do some reading.</p>



<p><strong>Musaddiq: </strong>Scott's Maps Library. It's nice, quiet and really close to my lecture halls.</p>



<p><strong>Guillaume:</strong> At Frost, I usually go work in the Reference Room. I like the atmosphere with the floor to ceiling bookshelves that remind me of an old library.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Best place for quiet space to work with a partner</h2>



<p><strong>Musaddiq:</strong> Group Study Rooms are ideal to work with partner in quiet place. It is private conversation friendly space so you can collaborate without any hassle.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignleft size-large is-resized"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Screenshot-2023-02-27-at-11.21.44-AM.png"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/Screenshot-2023-02-27-at-11.21.44-AM-1024x678.png" alt="" class="wp-image-23616" width="417" height="274" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Bronfman Library Study Room</figcaption></figure></div>


<p><strong>Taylor: </strong>If I need a quiet space to do work with a partner, I like to use the Steacie or Bronfman group rooms for the same reasons stated above.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignright size-full"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-2023-03-01-at-10.28.12-AM.png"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" width="513" height="338" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-2023-03-01-at-10.28.12-AM.png" alt="" class="wp-image-23727" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-2023-03-01-at-10.28.12-AM.png 513w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Screenshot-2023-03-01-at-10.28.12-AM-300x198.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 513px) 100vw, 513px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Scott Libary Study Room</figcaption></figure></div>


<p><strong>Subhay:</strong> Scott study rooms are the best place to work with a partner because they know the location and it's easier to book with longer open times so it can be accessed in late hours after everyone's classes.</p>



<p><br><strong>Mila:</strong> Bronfman/Scott study rooms - quiet enough but can still talk if needed and also private enough that you don't have to worry about others overhearing your conversations</p>



<p></p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Favourite Hidden Gems at York U Libraries</h2>



<p><strong>Taylor:</strong> My "hidden gem" place at the libraries would be the back-most cubicle space on the second floor of Bronfman Library. There is a nice view from the window, and there are fewer noise distractions than on the first floor.</p>



<p><strong>Musaddiq:</strong> Micro-reader room. The place is usually empty and so is basically your own private group study room that you do not have to book beforehand.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Untitled-design.png"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" width="1024" height="576" src="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Untitled-design-1024x576.png" alt="" class="wp-image-23737" srcset="https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Untitled-design-1024x576.png 1024w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Untitled-design-300x169.png 300w, https://www.library.yorku.ca/web/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/Untitled-design.png 1366w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Left to Right: Scott Library Microtext Room and Maps Library</figcaption></figure>



<p><strong>Subhay:</strong> 5th floor balcony study area which is not too quiet but quiet enough for you to work with a partner in relative silence and focus.<br>Mila: It wouldn't be a hidden gem otherwise (4th floor at Scott - it's super quiet and, if I'm not mistaken, also where the Loeb Classics editions are (call number is PA, I just forget which floor that is). I like to choose a study table, grab a couple off the shelf and flip through them.</p>



<p><em><strong>Watch our students on Instagram take you on a tour of their favourite spots</strong> <a href="https://www.instagram.com/stories/highlights/18287875540037823/">here.</a></em></p>



